      "type": "lab.html.Form",
      "content": "\u003Cmain class=\"content-horizontal-center\"\u003E\n  \u003Cdiv class=\"alert w-l text-left\"\u003E\n    \u003Cp class=\"alert alert-reminder\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIMPORTANT\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: To complete the study and submit your responses, you must copy the completion code below \u003Cstrong\u003EAND\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E click the button titled \u003Cstrong\u003EFinish study and submit data \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n  \u003Ch1\u003EDebrief\u003C\u002Fh1\u003E\n  \u003Cp\u003EWelcome to the end of the study! 🥳\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\n    \n    Thank you very much for participating in this session. Your participant ID has been recorded as: ${ this.state.prolific_pid }\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EYour \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompletion code\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E for Prolific is: \u003Ckbd style=\"font-size: 2rem;\"\u003ECC3C65C4\u003C\u002Fkbd\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\nPlease copy it now. Then use the button below to complete the study when you are ready, and finally paste the completion code into Prolific.\n\n  \u003Cform\u003E\n  \u003Cbutton type=\"submit\" class=\"black-btn\"\u003EFinish study and submit data\u003C\u002Fbutton\u003E\n  \u003C\u002Fform\u003E\n\n\u003Ch2\u003EContext\u003C\u002Fh2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe purpose of this study is to determine the difference in both raw reading performance and user preference when reading long news articles using a single scrolling page or a paginated style.\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EResearch in previous years has produced mixed results, indicating that there is either no difference between modes, or there is a positive effect which favours scrolling. However, advances in web standards have enabled simpler, dynamic methods of pagination which can be tailored to any screen, such as the one used in this study to separate the article into pages which load without buffering, and which merit renewed study. Additionally, some studies of digital reading have indicated that while displaying text in certain ways seems to help people to read faster or more efficiently, people's personal preference or reading experience may differ in important ways.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\nIf you have any additional comments to make about the study (for example, you noticed a bug or encountered other difficulties) please contact me at \u003Ca href=\"mailto:richardherlihy@gmail.com\"\u003Erichardherlihy@gmail.com\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIf you wish to withdraw your consent\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E, you can do so by closing this tab and returning the study on Prolific, instead of finalising your submission via the button above.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EThe article text which appears in this study was retrieved using The Guardian Open Platform API. © 2020 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\n\u003C!-- \u003Cform id=\"dataSubmission\"\u003E\n  \u003Cbutton type=\"submit\" class=\"black-btn\" for=\"dataSubmission\"\u003EFinish study and submit data\u003C\u002Fbutton\u003E\n\u003C\u002Fform\u003E --\u003E\n\n\u003C\u002Fdiv\u003E\n  \u003C\u002Fmain\u003E",
